<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Military     03-05 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Military,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Restructuring of Army Planned In Wake Of Corruption Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military chief plans a major
restructuring of senior echelons of the army in the wake of
allegations of widespread corruption and inefficiency, newspapers
reported Sunday.
   Several major newspapers quoted unnamed sources as saying Chief
of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa announced the impending changes last
Friday during a closed-door session of the Senate's defense
committee.
   The Manila Bulletin, The Manila Times and the Philippine Daily
Inquirer, quoted de Villa as saying the shakeup would effect
regional and division commanders. No date was given for the shakeup,
but the papers said it was expected to be announced in a few weeks.
   The Inquirer quoted the defense committee chairman, Sen. Ernesto
Maceda, as telling his colleagues that if de Villa did not move
soon, he himself would open formal investigations into the
allegations of corruption.
   The calls for a shakeup in the senior ranks have increased
following a series of embarassing incidents. They include the
November escape of Communist rebel commander Romulo Kintanar from a
Manila stockade; the takeover of a military headquarters by renegade
policemen last January and the recent arrest of several police and
military officers on car theft charges in Manila.
   Last week, Maceda charged that unidentified generals and colonels
were receiving thousands of dollars annually from criminal
syndicates in return for shielding them from arrest.
   Maceda also challenged military claims that government forces
have gained the upper hand in the 20-year war against the communist
New People's Army.
   Ten senior officers, including army commander Maj. Gen. Mariano
Adalem, are scheduled to retire this year. But the newspapers said
the shakeup will affect many senior officers not scheduled for
retirement.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
