<HEAD>Baker Arrives in Vienna to Usher in Arms Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III
arrived Sunday for meetings with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze and other NATO officials in a prelude to new European
talks on cutting conventional arms.
   Austrian Foreign Minister Alois Mock and U.S. Ambassador Henry A.
Grunwald welcomed at Baker at Vienna's Schwechat airport. He made no
statement upon arrival.
   Over three busy days, Baker will meet with Shevardnadze and
separately with several ministers of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization. He will make a speech Monday to herald the opening of
negotiations later in the week between the Western alliance and the
Warsaw Pact.
   Baker scheduled back-to-back meetings in Vienna on Sunday
afternoon with Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Varkonyi and Polish
Foreign Minister Marian Olechowski to get what a U.S. official
called ``a first-hand account of how reforms are going'' in the East
European countries and to determine ``where there may be opportunity
for U.S. cooperation.''
   On the flight to Vienna, with a refueling stop in Ireland, Baker
remained secluded in his sleeping quarters on the plane and did not
talk to the 17 reporters traveling with him.
   His session with Shevardnadze is expected to produce an agenda
for what would be Baker's first trip to the Soviet Union, probably
in late April or early May. It would mark a move by the Bush
administration to accelerate its review of policy toward Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Baker also assured two visiting delegations of American Jews on
Friday that human rights were on his agenda.
   The secretary of state is due to fly home Tuesday, and the
negotiations between NATO and the Warsaw Pact open Thursday.
   The NATO allies, under U.S. leadership, are pushing for sharp
reductions in the Warsaw Pact's edge of nearly 2-to-1 in tanks and
artillery. Their goal is to force the Soviet-led alliance down to
NATO levels and then cut about 5 percent to 10 percent on both sides.
   East and West are starting over after 15 years of futile
negotiations to reduce non-nuclear forces in Central Europe.
</TEXT>
