<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Suicide     03-05 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Suicide,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Commits Suicide Delayed for Emperor's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran of the Imperial Army who had planned to
commit suicide the day of Emperor Hirohito's funeral instead killed
himself last week to avoid interfering with the funeral, police said
Sunday.
   Toshio Muratani, 66, shot himself in the head with a pistol in a
Tokyo park Friday, a police spokesman said.
   The victim left a note saying he delayed his suicide until after
Hirohito's funeral so he would not ``inconvenience any parties
concerned,'' said the policeman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Muratani served as a lieutenant in the Japanese Imperial Army
during World War II. Japan fought the war in the name of the emperor.
   Hirohito, who died of cancer, was buried Feb. 24 in an elaborate
funeral attended by world leaders, including President Bush.
   Two former Japanese soldiers committed suicide to follow Hirohito
in death, earlier police reports said.
   Another veteran tried to kill himself on the southern island of
Kyushu by ritual disembowelment but survived. A police spokesman
said Sunday the veteran was ``doing well'' but was still
hospitalized with a cut through his small intestine.
</TEXT>
