<FILEID>AP-NR-03-05-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HighLife Bjt   03-05 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-High Life, Bjt,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lofty Light Bulb Changer Gets ``Weebles'' At Lincoln Memorial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaving desk-bound bureaucrats behind, Larry
Morrison has risen high in his government career, a man you can
really look up to.
   He's the guy who changes light bulbs at the top of the Washington
Monument.
   Every week or so, Morrison climbs a ladder about 515 feet above
ground to install a fresh bulb in the set of eight red airplane
warning lights that blink unceasingly at the apex of the popular
tourist attraction.
   Nothing to it, says Morrison, a 23-year veteran electrician for
the National Park Service.
   After all, Morrison works inside the monument, behind
18-inch-thick walls of granite and marble. He perches 15 feet above
the observation deck atop an aluminum extension ladder held steady
by an assistant.
   When he demonstrated his lofty job late last week, Morrison had
Raymond Hall, master Park Service electrician for the Washington
region, as his supervisor.
   Although the Washington Monument sways slightly in a stiff wind,
Morrison says the only time he feels queasy is when he climbs
outdoor scaffolding with the ``weebles and wobbles'' to change light
bulbs above the columns of the Lincoln Memorial.
   The bulbs that Morrison replaces at the Washington Monument are
500-watt spotlights that cost $70 apiece and last about a week or
two. They flash on and off continually from four pairs of holes on
each side of the pyramid-shaped monument peak.
   No airplane has ever struck the 555-foot Washington Monument,
which occupies airspace that is off-limits to planes landing or
taking off at nearby National Airport.
   However, seven people have died in suicides or accidental falls
down the monument's observation windows or elevator shaft since it
was opened to the public on Oct. 9, 1888.
   Bars were installed in the narrow windows on the 500-foot level
after they were used for the last two suicide leaps in 1926. Thick
safety glass was installed later. A high metal grill was erected
above the guard rail alongside the monument's 897 steps after the
last suicide down the shaft occurred in 1949.
   The inner stairway was closed to the public in 1976, except for
escorted tours downs the steps, because of vandalism and growing
congestion.
   An eighth death occurred at the monument in December 1982 when
police shot and killed Norman Mayer, an anti-nuclear demonstrator
who held the monument hostage for 10 hours claiming he would blow it
up with dynamite.
   Ironically, no one was killed during the entire 36 years it took
to build the monument.
</TEXT>
