<FIRST>r i AM-MarcosMania     03-05 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos Mania,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Countrymen in North Press for His Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FERDINAND, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of Ferdinand Marcos' fellow
northerners are clamoring for his return from exile and insisting
his death abroad could deepen their estrangement from the government
of President Corazon Aquino.
   ``There's going to be war,'' said Chit Guarin, a 27-year-old
medical technician who works near this village named in honor of the
favorite son of Ilocos Norte province. ``This is his home. Besides,
he is very bright, and he gave us a lot.''
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to allow Marcos, who was born in the
Ilocos Norte town of Sarrat, to return from exile in Hawaii, despite
claims from his family that the former president may soon die.
Marcos, 71, has been hospitalized since January with heart and
respiratory ailments.
   Here in Ilocos Norte and other Ilocano-speaking areas of the
north, the former president is still widely viewed as a hero.
   ``He is a blood brother and a province mate,'' said Pacita Juan,
46, a farmer.
   ``Many will become rebels (if Marcos dies in exile),'' said
Felicito Tamayo, mayor of the town of Marcos, which includes
Ferdinand village.
   Their views highlight the political estrangement many of the 6
million Ilocanos, the third-largest of more than 80 language groups
in the country, feel toward Mrs. Aquino.
   Government officials in Manila, 240 miles to the south, say most
Filipinos agree with Mrs. Aquino's stand toward Marcos, which she
says is based on national security. Marcos has lived in Hawaii since
he was overthrown in a popular uprising that swept Mrs. Aquino to
power three years ago.
   In Manila and other parts of this island nation, people generally
express contempt for Marcos.
   Many in this region, however, believe Marcos won the
fraud-tainted 1986 election against Mrs. Aquino, which was held
about two weeks before the uprising. In Ferdinand, which has about
400 residents, Mrs. Aquino received 10 votes in 1986.
   Residents said they were stunned by the news in 1986 their leader
was gone.
   ``Old people wept,'' recalled Junel Rosqueta, 20. ``They said,
`Marcos is gone; when will be come back?' All of them went to hear
Mass and to pray.''
   Melecio Duldulao, a village leader, said Ilocanos had come to
believe Marcos ``was president-for-life.''
   ``I had gotten used to him,'' he said. ``We have lost hope that
he will still be president now.''
   However, most people in this region say they accept the new
government while believing Marcos should be allowed to die here.
   ``It's not a question of being an Ilocano. It's a question of
being a Christian,'' said the Rev. Rock Bonoan, spokesman of the
Roman Catholic archdiocese. ``I would prefer that he (Marcos) be
given the chance to come back and die in his country. He is already
powerless. I don't see why many people are so afraid.''
   At the Marcos Agro-Industrial School, a state-funded elementary
and high school, fourth-grade students were asked if they wanted
Marcos to return. ``Yes!'' they shouted in unison.
   ``Marcos is not the cheater. Cory is the cheater,'' said
11-year-old Dennis Mamayan, referring to Mrs. Aquino by her nickname.
   ``We don't want what Cory is doing to Marcos. She is trying to
picture Marcos as a thief,'' said Arnel Ramirez, 7.
   Adults here fondly recall a visit Marcos paid to their remote,
mountain village during the 1950s when he was a member of the
Senate. Others recall the public works projects he provided for his
home province.
   ``Before 1963, no vehicles entered our place,'' said Helen
Abrigado. ``But after that, we had roads and electricity.''
   Most people interviewed brushed aside government allegations
Marcos embezzled billions of dollars during his administration.
Others said they did not care because Marcos boosted the province's
economic development.
</TEXT>
