<FIRST>u w AM-TowerSuccessor Bjt   03-05 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower Successor, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Said Ready to Move to Second Choice, Just in Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Senate rejects John Tower as defense
secretary, the White House is expected to move quickly to name a
replacement, even though it isn't acknowledging the possibility of
defeat.
   ``The president has told his staff and has told the nation that
he's not talking about successors, he's talking about getting his
nomination confirmed,'' said White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Still, administration aides and congressional sources say
privately that the president is mindful of the odds against winning
Tower's confirmation; and that the White House is determined not to
be caught off balance.
   The speculation is that Bush's would select a candidate who could
be confirmed quickly _ either someone now in government or someone
who in the recent past had been a Cabinet or sub-Cabinet official.
   Some Republicans in Congress have been pressing Bush to give the
job to his National Security Adviser, Brent Scowcroft, who is widely
respected on both sides of the aisle.
   In fact, if Bush was determined to keep Tower as part of his
administration, he could do a job swap, giving him Scowcroft's
present job _ which does not require Senate confirmation and which
is not in the military line of command.
   Although Scowcroft's name has been heard most frequently in
recent White House speculation, there is no shortage of candidates.
   Among them:
   _ Sen. John Warner of Virginia, senior Republican on the Senate
Armed Services Committee. A former secretary of the Navy, Warner
would sail through the Senate if nominated. However, a big political
minus to Republicans would be the loss of a Senate seat, since
Democratic Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles would surely fill the
vacancy with a member of his own party.
   _Former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld. Now a corporate
executive, Rumsfeld was former President Ford's defense secretary in
1975-77. He is mentioned frequently as a likely contender for the
post, but his support of Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas against Bush in
last year's Republican primaries could work against him.
   _Former Rep. Jack Edwards of Alabama. He was the senior
Republican on the Appropriations defense subcommittee for many years
and was highly regarded for his knowledge of the defense budget and
for his skill in arguing defense issues.
   _Drew Lewis, former Transportation Secretary. The president of
Union Pacific Corp. has become a GOP workhorse with a string of
high-level assignments and would bring a management perspective to
the job. He was in President Reagan's first Cabinet and most
recently was co-chairman of the Federal Economic Commission, which
tried to tackle the problem of the budget deficit.
   _Norman Augustine, chief executive officer of Martin-Marietta
Corp. He reportedly was offered, and turned down, the chance to be
deputy defense secretary, but might view the No. 1 spot differently.
He has been involved in developing various proposals for defense
modernization. However, his lack of previous government service
could be a liability.
   When asked whether Bush has considered alternatives, whether
anyone on his staff has considered alternatives, or whether the
White House personnel office has done any preliminary work in such a
direction, Fitzwater is emphatic.
   ``To my knowledge and under every instruction that I've been
given by everybody of any authority, the answer to that no, no, no
and no,'' says the presidential spokesman.
   But analysts and leading Republicans in Congress suggest
otherwise.
   ``If there hasn't been at least one session in the Oval Office to
bat around alternatives to Tower, then they're nuts. They've got to
have a contingency plan,'' said Norman Ornstein of the conservative
American Enterprise Institute.
   ``George Bush has to come forward with someone very quickly who
can be confirmed quickly,'' if Tower loses, Ornstein said,
suggesting that additional delays in getting his defense team in
place are ``the last thing he wants to do.''
   Sen. Phil Gramm, D-Texas, an outspoken Tower defender, said he
believed ``several people'' might be considered as backup candidates
for Tower, but that the White House has given no signal it is
wavering in its support for Tower.
   Rep. Lynn Martin, R-Ill., a former member of the House Armed
Services Committee who was a top Bush campaign adviser, said she
assumes the president's senior staff has given consideration to a
successor to Tower even if Bush has not.
   ``Of course, they'll have alternatives ready. That's what staff
is for,'' she said in an interview. ``You always plan to the
possibility of losing.''
   Mrs. Martin said Bush was entirely proper in forbidding his staff
to talk about possible backup candidates. ``It is not the
appropriate time,'' she said.
</TEXT>
