<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     03-05 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress To Focus On Tower Nomination, Wright Ethics Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fledgling 101st Congress, with no major
legislation to consider, will be dominated this week by highly
partisan squabbles _ one behind tightly sealed doors and the other
in the glare of television.
   The only significant legislative activity will come in the Senate
Labor and Human Resources Committee, which will begin writing a bill
to raise the $3.35 minimum wage to at least $4.25 and perhaps as
much as $4.65 an hour.
   The Bush administration supports an increase to no more than
$4.25 _ and only then if workers are exempted until they have been
on the job for at least six months.
   With the nation looking on, the Democratic-controlled Senate will
resume debate Monday on the nomination of former Sen. John G. Tower,
a Republican, to be secretary of defense. A final vote is likely
this week, and despite President Bush's pleas, no Democrat has
announced support for Tower. No Republican has come out against him.
   On the other side of the Capitol, a 12-member committee evenly
divided between the two parties will attempt to wrap up its
investigation of House Speaker Jim Wright of Texas, the most
powerful Democrat in government. The ethics committee has been
looking into Wright's behavior for nine months, and has diligently
guarded against news leaks of its private discussions.
   The panel is considering six allegations against Wright. Most of
the attention has centered on assertions that he improperly used his
office to produce and sell a book on which he made $55,000, in part
by selling the book to special interests. He also is accused of
having lobbied improperly on behalf of Texas savings institutions.
   The speaker says he is confident that he will be vindicated.
   A finding that Wright violated House ethics standards would send
the matter to the full House. Regardless of the outcome, Republicans
already have vowed that Wright will be their chief target in the
1990 elections.
   A Senate vote against Tower would make history. Never before has
the Senate rejected the Cabinet nominee of a president entering his
first term.
   Tower, an acknowledged expert on military matters, is under fire
for what some senators view as a drinking problem and because be
sold his advice to the defense industry after leaving government as
a senior arms negotiator.
   Tower, a former chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
served 23{ years in the Senate. The depth of his problem became
clear when all 11 Democrats on the panel opposed him and only the 9
Republicans voted for him.
   Another Bush nominee, former Education Secretary William Bennett,
is likely to have a much easier time.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to vote Thursday to
recommend confirmation of Bennett to head the federal government's
battle against illegal drugs.
   Bennett, who has the warm endorsement of Sen. Joseph Biden Jr.,
D-Del., chairman of the committee, told the panel he plans to target
casual drug users as well as drug distributors.
   The Senate will vote Tuesday on confirming career diplomat Thomas
Pickering to be U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
   Pickering has faced some criticism because while serving as
ambassador to Israel, he received a document from a Central American
leader offering $1 million worth of military equipment to the rebels
fighting the leftist government in Nicaragua. The letter, received
at a time when the law barred U.S. military aid to the rebels, was
delivered directly by Pickering to National Security Council aide
Oliver North.
   Until committees begin churning out legislation, Congress has
little to do except nominations and housekeeping measures.
   Leaders of Congress and the Bush administration may begin
negotiations late in the week aimed at producing a budget for the 12
months that begin next Oct. 1.
   Bush has proposed a $1.16 trillion spending plan that he says
would reduce the budget deficit below the $100 billion maximum
allowed by law. Democrats complain that the president's plan leaves
to Congress the tough decisions on which programs to cut to meet
that deficit target.
   Hanging over the budget discussions is Bush's pledge not to raise
taxes. Democratic leaders say any workable plan must include some
tax increases but they are not about to take the first step unless
they are joined by the president.
</TEXT>
