<FILEID>AP-NR-03-05-89 1347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-ChicagoMayoral     03-05 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Mayoral Candidates Have Democratic Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The front-runner for next month's mayoral election
is a Democrat, his closest pursuer was a Democrat as recently as
December, and the No. 3 man in the race was Democratic county
chairman just 18 months ago.
   An out-of-towner might ask what these guys _ Richard M. Daley,
Alderman Tim Evans and former county chairman-turned Republican
Edward Vrdolyak _ are fighting about?
   But Chicagoans aren't surprised.
   ``When you have only one functioning party choosing one
candidate, the other guys get blocked, then frustrated, then go off
on their own and call themselves something else,'' explains Mike
Royko, a veteran political observer and columnist for the Chicago
Tribune.
   Evans, a black, ran as a Democrat when he was elected alderman
and is now running for mayor as an independent. Vrdolyak entered the
GOP primary at the last minute as a write-in candidate, and even
though he got 80 percent of the white vote in his unsuccessful
independent mayoral challenge in 1987, he is regarded as third in
the race now.
   The city's last Republican mayor was William Hale ``Big Bill''
Thompson, a three-term mayor so brazen about his alliance with
gangsters that his portrait hung in the headquarters of the Al
Capone gang.
   Thompson was eased out in 1931 by Anton ``Pushcart Tony'' Cermak,
credited with bringing to Chicago the modern political machine: a
coalition of ethnic voters bound by the principle of self-interest _
everybody gets something.
   What followed was a succession of politicians as diverse as
Daley's father, the late Richard J. Daley _ the last of the big-city
``bosses'' who died in 1976 _ and Harold Washington, a reformer
whose 1983 election as the city's first black mayor and whose death
just months into his second term in 1987 altered the course of
Chicago's Democratic Party.
   ``If the old man (Richard J. Daley) were alive, there's a lot
about the party he wouldn't recognize, even if his son winds up at
the top of it,'' said Eugene Kennedy, a Loyola University professor
and author of ``Himself,'' a biography of the elder Daley.
   ``In his day, a Democrat was a Democrat first and whatever else
he was came second.''
   Washington changed that by winning with little more than a single
racial bloc, Kennedy said. The town is about 40 percent white, 40
percent black and 20 percent Hispanic and other minorities.
   ``And what you see now, essentially, are three men _ two white
and one black _ relying on the same strategy, trying to do
essentially the same thing,'' he added.
   Washington's 1983 election came after a racially charged
campaign. But his ability to govern fairly eased the fears of many
whites who opposed him, and he was re-elected in 1987 with
significantly less strife.
   The younger Daley last week became the first white to oust an
incumbent black mayor in a major U.S. city by defeating Eugene
Sawyer, who filled in after Washington's death. But their primary
campaign was surprisely free of rancor and appeals to race,
considering the racially split voting.
   Daley, 46, three-term Cook County state's attorney, received
significant support from liberals and an emerging Hispanic bloc,
though the lion's share of his support came from many of the same
white ethnics who made his father mayor for 21 years.
   Black voter turnout was depressed, according to some estimates,
by as much as 20 percent in wards that had proved crucial to
Washington's victories.
   Most political observers laid the blame for that at the feet of
Evans, 45, who waged a long and often-bitter battle with Sawyer to
be recognized among blacks as Washington's righful heir. Sawyer was
elected acting mayor after Washington's death largely because of the
support of white aldermen.
   ``That split still exists, and that's the reason Daley likely
will win April 4,'' said Lu Palmer, an influential black political
activist and radio commentator. ``Many, many Sawyer supporters are
saying that Evans and his allies are the reason for Sawyer's loss,
and many are saying they will not vote for Evans.
   ``People are saying Vrdolyak will split the white vote with Daley
... but I say Vrdolyak won't have much of an impact. Why should
white Democrats cross over and vote for Vrdolyak? They've already
got their candidate.''
   Paul Kleppner, a political science professor and author, put it
this way: ``Almost everybody in the city may still think of
themselves as Democrats, but now, most of them are black Democrats
or white Democrats.''
</TEXT>
