<FIRST>r a AM-BabyKilled     03-05 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Killed,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Acquitted In Killing Of Baby</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANITOWOC, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school cheerleader was acquitted of
murdering her newborn boy by slashing his throat, after she
testified that he was not breathing and she tried to give him a
tracheotomy to help him breath.
   ``I'm just glad it's finally over and I can see all my friends
again,'' the 15-year-old from the Valders area said after her
acquittal Saturday on the most serious charge against her.
   A Manitowoc County Circuit Court jury deliberated more than four
hours before ruling the girl was innocent of the juvenile code
murder charge but guilty of trying to conceal the infant's body in a
plastic bag.
   When the verdict was announced, the defendant slumped onto her
attorney's shoulder and said ``thank you.''
   Judge Fred Hazelwood said the court must decide within 30 days
what action to take on the concealment conviction. The state
children's code, which keeps the girl's name officially
confidential, allows several options, including counseling and
community confinement.
   Until that decision, Hazelwood ordered her to remain in a foster
home, but he lifted an order that prevented her from having contact
with friends.
   The defendant, a sophomore at Valders High School and a member of
its cheerleading squad, said she found testifying at the six-day
trial difficult.
   ``I was nervous, but I actually got a chance to say for myself
what happened,'' she told reporters outside the courtroom.
   The girl testified she gave birth in a basement bathroom Dec. 28
but the infant was not breathing.
   After trying to revive him with mouth-to-mouth resuscitation
which she learned in a class on cardiopulmonary respiration, she
attempted a tracheotomy _an incision in the throat _ to open the
infant's windpipe but that also failed.
   She said she then placed the body in a plastic bag and dropped it
in the yard of a neighbor.
   District Attorney E. James Fitzgerald said in his closing
arguments that the physical evidence, including other cut and stab
marks on the infant's body, showed the girl really was trying to
kill the baby.
   ``Nice people do bad things; sometimes they do crimes,''
Fitzgerald said.
   But defense attorney Ron Kaminski said the prosecution managed to
prove only that the girl had a baby.
   ``Where is the evidence of death after life?'' he asked. ``As
horrible as it is, this is not a murder.''
   He conceded that ``everything she did was bad news'' but added
his client did not intend to kill the boy. He said prosecution
testimony had ``glaring ommissions'' and that the entire prosecution
was based on ``manipulation and speculation.''
</TEXT>
