<FIRST>r a AM-Ex-WifeSlain     03-05 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ex-Wife Slain,0449</SECOND>
<UNK>State Inmate On Pass Accused of Slaying Ex-Wife</UNK>
<DATELINE>MISHAWAKA, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate on a day pass from a state
prison beat his ex-wife to death with a shotgun while her neighbors
watched, authorities said. She apparently was unaware that he was
being temporarily released.
   Alan Matheney, 38, was arrested about two hours after the beating
Saturday and charged with murdering his ex-wife, Lisa Marie Bianco,
29, said Cpl. Kevin Lockhart of the Mishawaka Police Department.
   Matheney, who wa serving time in prison for assaulting Bianco two
years ago, was being held Sunday at the St. Joseph County Jail in
South Bend.
   Prison officials said Matheney was released Saturday on his first
pass since being sentenced to an eight-year term in Nov. 1987 for
assaulting Bianco. The pass limited his travel to the Indianapolis
area, 40 miles southwest of the Correctional Industrial Complex in
Pendleton where he was being housed.
   Authorities said Matheney instead traveled 120 miles north to
Mishawaka, where police received reports Saturday afternoon of a
beating at his ex-wife's home.
   ``There were several witnesses,'' said Lockhart. ``It's kind of
the low-rent district, so nobody probably wanted to get involved.
... There's a lot of elderly people.''
   When officers arrived, they found Bianco lying in a yard. Police
said she was bludgeoned to death with the butt of a rifle.
   ``She was struck several times while standing and several times
when she fell,'' Lockhart said. The force of the beating broke the
shotgun in half.
   Matheney was seen leaving in a vehicle and was apprehended
unarmed about five or 10 miles away, Lockhart said.
   Charles Miller, superintendent of the prison complex where
Matheney was held, and Mishawaka Police Cpl. Rick Hurley said that
as far as they knew, Bianco was not notified her ex-husband would be
released for a day and that such notification was not required.
   It is required only when a crime victim or other citizen makes a
specific request to be notified before a inmate gets out of prison
for good, not just on a temporary pass, officials said.
   Matheney was eligible for up to a 48-hour pass. Correction
officials granted the shorter pass to gradually expose him to
freedom to ensure he could handle it, Miller said.
   He said he had no idea if there would be any policy changes
following the incident. ``Policy is something that's set by the
department (of correction), not individual institutions,'' he said.
   Police Cpl. Eugene Trippel said an autopsy on Bianco was planned.
He had no information Sunday on when she was married to Matheney or
whether the couple had children.
</TEXT>
