<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0708,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fundamentalists Call For Escalated Strikes; 17 Arabs Reported Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 17 reported wounded. Pickup
8th pvs, `In Nablus...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen Palestinians were reported shot and
wounded in clashes with soldiers in the occupied territories Sunday
as Moslem fundamentalists declared a week of increased resistance to
mark an Islamic holiday.
   Palestinians erected barricades and burned tires in Gaza City,
shouting ``God is great! There is no God but one God!'' and pelting
Israeli troops with rocks, an Arab reporter said.
   Youths burned an Israeli flag and a three-foot wooden statue of
an Israeli soldier, the reporter said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Hospital officials said 12 Palestinians were shot and wounded in
stone-throwing clashes in Gaza City, Khan Yunis, Rafah and the
Jabaliya refugee camp, where the Palestinian rebellion began nearly
15 months ago. All are in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   The wounded included two boys from Khan Yunis, aged 12 and 13,
who were shot in the stomach, and a 12-year-old from Rafah hit in
the shoulder, the doctors said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   Arab reports said a 50-year-old Palestinian was wounded in the
leg in the West Bank city of Nablus and a 25-year-old from nearby
Askar refugee camp was shot in the hand.
   The army could not confirm the reports but said another
Palestinian was shot after he stabbed and lightly wounded an Israeli
soldier in the arm and that two other Arabs were shot and wounded in
a clash in Ramallah.
   In Nablus, the army maintained the 10th straight day of a curfew,
requiring the 120,000 residents to remain in their homes.
   Troops also raided homes and forced hundreds of people to sit in
the street while their homes were searched, an Arab reporter said,
adding that some area residents were ``hysterical.''
   The curfew followed the Feb. 24 death of an Israeli paratrooper
who was killed by a cement block dropped from a rooftop.
   At least 388 Palestinians and 17 Israelis have been killed in the
Palestinian uprising against the 21-year Israeli rule of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The clashes came after the Moslem Hamas movement called for
strikes to mark Al Israa wal Meraj holiday, which was Sunday.
   The holiday celebrates the prophet Mohammed's journey to
Jerusalem, during which Moslems believe he ascended to heaven from
the site marked by the Dome of the Rock in the walled Old City.
   Hamas urged strikes Tuesday, Thursday and Friday, challenging the
pro-PLO Unified National Leadership of the Uprising, which called
for strikes Monday, Wednesday and Friday. The Hamas move, announced
in leaflets distributed Sunday, indicated a rift between the groups.
   While the Palestine Liberation Organization appears ready for
accept separate Arab and Jewish states to end the Middle East
conflict, Moslem fundamentalists have declared they want an Islamic
state made up of Israel and the occupied territories.
   Arab reports suggested Hamas also was upset that PLO chief Yasser
Arafat reportedly gave the Unites States information on radical
Palestinian groups in Europe. Some of these, such as Ahmed Jibril's
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, are
known to have links with Hamas, Palestinian reports said.
   In Jerusalem, a government official said PLO chief Yasser Arafat
has proposed talks with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and indicated
a willingness to have U.N. or multinational forces in the occupied
lands if they became an indpendent Palestinian state.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Arafat
made the proposal in a meeting last month in Tunisia with Rep. Wayne
Owens, D-Utah, and that news of the meeting was part of ``routine
reports'' on the 3-month-old U.S. dialogue with the PLO.
   Several telephone calls to Owen's homes in Utah and Washington
were not answered.
</TEXT>
