<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Pilots Bjt   03-05 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Eastern Pilots Foresee End Of 60-Year-Old Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORAL GABLES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tim McCord has logged more than 1
million miles in the air in 17 years as an Eastern Airlines
co-pilot, and now he's walking his first picket line, in sympathy
with striking mechanics and ramp service workers.
   ``At one time, Eastern was it. It had the best people and the
brightest future,'' McCord said Saturday night. ``I don't think I
have a future with Eastern anymore. I may have flown my last flight
as an Eastern pilot.''
   At the Air Line Pilots Association offices in the Miami suburb of
Coral Gables, pilots say their decision to back the 2-day-old
Machinists union strike could force the carrier into bankruptcy.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's owner, Texas Air Corp., has
predicted a widespread job action by the 3,500 union pilots would
drive the airline under.
   ``We called his bluff,'' said ALPA spokesman J.B. Stokes. ``He
thought he'd get enough pilots to keep a quarter of the flights.
Where are those pilots? They're on the picket lines.''
   Stokes said fewer than 1 percent of the APLA members _ 20 or 30
pilots _ decided to fly. He said replacing pilots may be near
impossible, since relatively few available pilots are licensed to
operate commercial jetliners, and ALPA last year won a court order
prohibiting Texas Air from training non-union crews for strike
contingencies.
   ``I don't want to sound elitist, but in time they can replace the
Machinists,'' said Stokes. ``It's a far more difficult task to find
people to fly the aircraft.''
   Stokes said he believes other airlines will quickly hire most of
ALPA members if they lose their jobs at Eastern. There is a
nationwide shortage of airline pilots, but some stay with Eastern
because they have built up seniority.
   The unusual alliance between ALPA and the 8,500 Machinists at
Eastern was prompted more by pilots' dissatisfaction with management
practices and promises than by unity with Machinists, who
traditionally have had strained relations with the pilots' union,
said Stokes. Pilots did not participate in Eastern strikes in 1958
and 1966.
   Stokes and other pilots say their grievances center on
management's pressures on flight crews since Texas Air acquired the
60-year-old airline in 1986. Allegations include allowing planes to
fly without making needed repairs or removing captains from flights
for deciding to ground a plane deemed unsafe, said Stokes.
   The ALPA walkout was assured when a last-minute contract offered
Friday by Lorenzo sought more than $64 million in wage concessions
from pilots and did not include a job-protection clause in the event
of bankruptcy, said Stokes, who claims ALPA members have already
given up nearly $500 million in salaries and benefits. Currently, an
Eastern 727 captain earns about $90,000 a year, nearly 30 percent
below the industry standard, he said.
   ``We had to figure out what was in the best interest of the
pilots,'' Stokes said. ``Trying to keep Eastern flying was not the
answer.''
   ``It breaks my heart to walk the picket lines and see what has
become of the airline I once loved,'' said flight engineer Bill
Hodgson, who has worked for the airline for 18 years. ``The second
definition of trust is assured hope. Do I have assured hope I will
fly again for Eastern? At this point I have to say no.''
</TEXT>
