<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government is taking its savings
bonds pitch on the fast track.
   The Treasury Department has agreed to pay $3,500 for advertising
on a white Chevrolet Beretta, which is expected to make its debut at
the Charlotte Motor Speedway on April 15, said James Gianfagna,
marketing director for the government bonds.
   ``I want to become the best salesman for U.S. savings bonds that
they have,'' said the man who will be behind the wheel, Aloysius
``Cappy'' Coleman Jr. of Jersey City. ``It's quite a unique
opportunity. I mean, who hears about bonds anymore?''
   Coleman, 44, owns Capgar Racing Inc., an automotive company in
Jersey City.
   He and his marketing director were searching for car sponsors
``and I said, `How about the government?' We laughed, but wrote a
letter to them. Then we heard back that they were interested.''
   The Treasury Department has not approved the car's exterior
graphics, but they might include an eagle and a picture of a U.S.
savings bond, Coleman said. Uniforms will be white, with red and
blue accents.
   Coleman still seeks a co-sponsor willing to spend $500,000 on his
automobile. And the government is just a little choosy about who it
wants to share the car with.
   ``We can't have alcoholic beverages or foreign companies.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>URBANA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every night is opening night at the Spice
Room, a gourmet restaurant operated by University of Illinois
students.
   Customers dare not become too fond of the beef a la Saint Moritz
or the ricotta pie with chocolate and liqueur. They never will be
served again.
   ``We never repeat anything,'' said Jane Myers, who supervises 25
seniors in the restaurant management class. ``Each student takes
great pride in creating a unique menu.''
   The Spice Room, open to the public, serves on Tuesday and
Thursday evenings. A five-course meal, including wine, costs about
$10.
   Each night, a different student is in charge of selecting the
menu and supervising the other workers. That means selecting food,
buying it, timing preparation, and making a profit.
   A sample of every dish is prepared in advance to make sure the
recipe will work.
   ``What if my clam chowder curdles?'' said Eric Rose. ``I'd be in
trouble.''
   Customers fill out detailed evaluation cards, and Myers reviews
the comments with students at the end of the week. Everything is
graded, from the placement of silverware to the visual appeal of the
food on the plate.
   ``They'll say the waiter's shoes weren't polished or something
was cold,'' said Myers. ``But most people really like it.''
</TEXT>
