<FIRST>u i AM-Venezuela-Survivors 1stLd-Writethru   03-05 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Survivors, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0698,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuelan Family Ducks From Bullets During The Rioting</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, ``I want...' to reflect new government casualty
count. Pickup 4th graf, `The army...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hernandez family had not slept at
home for a week.
   They camped out in the hallway of their housing project, ducking
the bullets, as soldiers battled with snipers in the mud and brick
homes and rundown apartment complexes in the hills west of Caracas.
   ``I want my son back. I don't agree with what they've done,''
said Marina Hernandez inside her apartment Saturday, after a week of
nationwide unrest that left at least 246 people dead, by government
count. Thousands were reported detained.
   The army knocked on the family's door Friday, while Hermes, a
16-year-old high school student, was taking a shower.
   ``They dragged him away naked. We went to the military bases
looking for him. At Conejo Blanco (an army base outside Caracas),
they said he wasn't there and even if he was, they wouldn't let us
see him,'' said Mrs. Hernandez, the mother of three. ``All we can do
is wait.''
   Officials put the number of detentions at 1,000, but news reports
have said several thousand were taken into custody. Most of the
detained were taken to military installations, officials said.
   The rioting began Monday and was sparked by increases in bus
fares _ part of a government austerity plan. The violence began in
Caracas but spread quickly to other cities.
   On Tuesday, the government imposed martial law across the
country, giving the military the right to detain anyone on sight. It
eliminated rights to access to a lawyer or contact with family
members.
   Officials refused to say how long the martial law would go on.
   ``They're going to be in there for a good long while,'' said
Jesus Regalado, a member of an intelligence police unit, DISIP.
   Many arrests came from the winding streets of neighborhoods such
as the Hernandez's, where chickens and babies run through dirt
courtyards past graffiti-covered walls.
   ``Thank God my other brother, Miguel, wasn't here. They were just
taking anybody they could. They took away good boys from this
building,'' said Norma Hernandez, 22, sitting on a bed with her
mother.
   On the wall above them were bullet holes, proof of fierce gun
battles between army units posted on a hill above the complex and
snipers inside the building.
   Miguel and his father, Abdon, work as hospital janitors and were
not home when soldiers searched the building Friday, said Norma
Hernandez.
   She said fighting had quieted down since then, but sporadic
firing continued through Saturday.
   Officials cut off electricity to the building, but Mrs. Hernandez
said, ``we can't leave because if the military comes again and
nobody's home, they'll destroy our home.''
   ``We've been sleeping in the hall all week,'' she said.
   She said she didn't know who the snipers were.
   ``We can see the boys firing out the windows. But who knows where
they're getting their weapons?'' she said.
   Military spokesmen have said snipers were been using pistols and
Belgian FAL automatic rifles, which are also used by the army.
   ``I don't know how this is going to end,'' Norma Hernandez said.
   ``I think the government is going to send in an assault. There's
going to be a response, and it's going to end in a massacre. Because
when the army comes in, they don't have good intentions.''
</TEXT>
