<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Scene     03-05 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Scene,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>It's No Honeymoon Waiting for Eastern Flights at LaGuardia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos and Ileana Rodriguez spent the first day
of their honeymoon hanging around an airport terminal Sunday waiting
for their grounded Eastern Airlines flight to take off.
   The Rodriguezes, of Fairview, N.J., got married Saturday night
and had planned to take a 7:40 a.m. Eastern flight to Puerto Rico
from Newark Airport in New Jersey.
   But when they called the airline, they were told to show up for a
12:10 p.m. flight from LaGuardia Airport. Once at the airport, they
were told the flight was grounded because there were no pilots to
fly the planes.
   ``I'm very disappointed and disgusted by the whole ordeal,'' said
Rodriguez.
   Eastern flights nationwide all but came to a halt Saturday, when
8,500 machinists struck the carrier. With pilots joining the
walkout, only about 85 of more than 1,000 flights took off Saturday.
   Eastern expected to run about 125 flights nationwide Sunday.
   Outside the Eastern terminal at LaGuardia, several pilots who
were among the 40 pickets said no pilots had crossed the picket
lines.
   ``All flights canceled! All flights canceled!'' the strikers
shouted.
   But one Eastern flight made it into the air.
   Flight 19, bound for Miami and Bogota, Colombia, sat on the
runway for three hours with the passengers aboard before it left
about 1 p.m., according to Jim Ashlock, an Eastern spokesman in
Miami. Many passengers were to board a cruise liner in Miami, he
said.
   Wendy Margulis, of Newtown, Conn., whose daughter was aboard,
said a pilot told her the flight was delayed because the co-pilot
had walked off the plane. Ashlock said he did not know if that were
the case.
   Outside the terminal, a picket hoisted a sign reading, ``The
mechanics are out here, who's fixing the planes?''
   Other passengers said they came to the airport after Eastern
agents had told them by phone that their flights to Miami would
leave.
   Debbie Vasilevich of Poughkeepsie, who arrived at LaGuardia with
a Pan Am ticket, said: ``I'm so glad I'm not on Eastern.''
   But other would-be Eastern passengers were good-humored as they
jammed the Pan American World Airways counter.
   Salomeja Valukas, of New Haven, Conn., who was headed for Miami,
said she called Eastern on Saturday night and an agent informed her
the airline could not tell her anything.
   ``You have to go to the airport,'' she quoted the agent as
saying. ``What can I do? I went through the war in Europe. There are
worse things in life.''
   The number of passengers on the Pan Am shuttle to Boston and
Washington was double its normal weekend volume, said Pan Am
spokesman Jeffery Kriendler. He said the airline expects to use 64
shuttle planes Sunday with a capacity of 153 passengers each.
   By 11 a.m., Eastern agents stopped issuing tickets to travelers
who had booked in advance. The Eastern terminal at Kennedy
International Airport was a ghost town, with about a dozen pickets
trudging in the rain and a sign on the door that said:
   ``To our customers. We deeply regret the disruption in our flight
schedule. Our personnel will make every effort to assist you in
making alternative arrangements.''
</TEXT>
