<FIRST>r a BC-PajamaGame     03-05 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pajama Game,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY City Opera Musical Comedy Season Looks Bright</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Pajama Game'' is the bright, wide-awake,
fourth entry in the New York City Opera's annual season of musical
comedies. The wonderful Richard Adler-Jerry Ross songs sound
glorious played by an orchestra bigger than will fit into any
Broadway pit.
   Not all the performers at the New York State Theater are as
endearing as those in the 1957 movie of the 1954 Broadway hit, but
they're good. The songs and Theodore Pappas' choreography, with
signature touches from Bob Fosse's original dances, carry the
ebullient day.
   Judy Kaye is charming as Babe, head of the grievance committee of
the Sleep Tite pajama factory. Her voice is rich and full. Miss
Kaye, who hasn't sung with the New York City Opera before, last was
heard here in the modern opera ``Desire under the Elms.'' A year ago
she was equally as effective in ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' for
which she won a supporting actress Tony.
   Richard Muenz sings the factory superintendent, Sid. He and Babe
run into differences over a proposed 7{-cent raise but also fall in
love. Muenz has sung on Broadway, in ``Chess'' and as Lancelot in
``Camelot,'' but he sounds operatically trained, much stiffer than
the way John Raitt sang Sid.
   Still, his ``Hey There'' and their duets of ``Small Talk'' and
``There Once Was a Man'' are winning.
   Lenora Nemetz as Gladys is the feisty dancer in the show's dance
plums _ ``Steam Heat'' and ``Hernando's Hideaway.'' Those numbers
made Carol Haney a star. Miss Nemetz's fresh, bright dancing pays
homage to her and to Fosse and brings enjoyment every minute.
   Avery Saltzman is in a similar state, as Hines, the time-study
man in love with flirty Gladys. Saltzman isn't intrinsically funny,
just walking across a stage, as Eddie Foy Jr. was. But he's funny
when the plot calls for it, as when he tries on sabotaged pajamas or
in his fervent duet about Gladys with a secretary (Brooks Almy),
``I'll Never Be Jealous Again.''
   Peter Howard, whose credits include seven Broadway shows,
conducted. The six dancing couples and the chorus of women singers
are fetching in their 1957 full skirts designed by Marjorie McCown.
Michael Anania created bright sets.
   Miss Kaye's husband, David Green, who has had featured roles on
``Kate and Allie'' and ``One Life To Live,'' plays Prez, the
factory's womanizer.
   The book, in which reedy-voiced Steve Pudenz plays an
unsympathetic boss named Hasler, was written by George Abbott and
Richard Bissell, whose family had a pajama factory in Dubuque, Iowa.
It's based on Bissell's novel, ``7{ Cents.''
   ``The Pajama Game'' will run at the New York State Theater
through April 16. The season is dedicated to Lawrence A. Wien, who
died in December. He and his wife gave the New York City Opera the
money to do five musical comedy seasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
