<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Stalin Bjt   03-05 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Stalin, Bjt,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ukrainians Mark Anniversary of Stalin's Death By Forming Anti-Stalin
Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>KIEV, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 Ukrainians on Sunday marked the
36th anniversary of dictator Josef Stalin's death by forming a group
to expose his crimes, but they saved much of their energy for what
they see as current repression.
   ``Our aim is to fight against modern Stalinism,'' Villan
Ochakievsky, a Ukrainian activist freed from imprisonment in a
mental hospital last summer, told the crowd.
   ``Stalinism Lives!'' shouted Volodimir Solopenko. He told the
crowd four activists were arrested in this Ukrainian capital 10 days
ago for organizing a legal demonstration. One of the four was beaten
in jail and sent to a hospital, where he has begun a hunger strike,
Solopenko alleged.
   More than 2,000 people heard speakers express similar sentiments
in Moscow in a rally organized by Memorial, the parent group of the
one founded Sunday in Kiev. The Moscow crowd, huddling under a
canopy in Gorky Park, applauded vigorously when literary critic Yuri
Koryakin linked Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev to Stalinism and
demanded his resignation.
   ``Democracy Yes! Stalinism No!'' one banner at the Moscow meeting
read. ``For a Society Without Executioners and Victims,'' read
another.
   More than 100 groups nationwide are campaigning for construction
of monuments to Stalin's victims, but they also take up a wide range
of issues.
   The 5,000 people gathered in front of Kiev's Republic Stadium
formed the new group. The meeting ended with adoption of resolutions
calling for a national day of mourning for the victims of Stalin and
opening of secret police archives.
   The group also demanded legalization of the Ukrainian Catholic
Church, rehabilitation and compensation of dissidents and the
release of Ukrainian human rights activist Anatoly Ilchenko from
imprisonment in a psychiatric hospital.
   Stalin, who ruled from 1924 until his death on March 5, 1953, has
been blamed for the arrests, killings, or other repression of 40
million Soviets.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev resumed a campaign begun by
Premier Nikita S. Khrushchev to clear the names of Stalin's victims
and acknowledge the extent of the dictator's crimes.
   Security agents did not interfere with the four-hour meeting.
   Kiev's prosecutor, Vladimir I. Shevchenko, made a reference at
the rally to a mass grave at Bykovnia, a village outside Kiev.
Activists say as many as 300,000 bodies were dumped in the mass
grave. Three government commissions had blamed the Nazis, who
occupied the village from 1941 to 1943, but villagers say the
killers were Stalin's secret police.
   Shevchenko said investigators had found evidence that people
buried at Bykovnia disappeared in 1937-38. But he said officials
still believe the site may also contain victims of the Nazis.
   Another speaker alleged that sand and bones from another
suspected mass grave of Stalin's victims, at Poltava in the Ukraine,
are being processed into concrete for apartment buildings.
   The deputy chief of the Kiev Communist Party, Stanislav
Martinyuk, won applause for joining the call to open government
archives. But the audience was less receptive when he said the party
was a victim of Stalin. Martinyuk said 94 of the 120 members of the
Ukrainian Central Committee of Stalin's time were ``repressed.''
   In answer to questions from the crowd, Shevchenko claimed to have
no power to free the four activists arrested 10 days ago, but
promised to investigate and protest if the charge _ hooliganism _
proves false.
   ``We have a Soviet society of laws,'' he said, using a favorite
phrase of reformers. When the prosecutor said Ukrainian officials
already abide by the law, some crowd members laughed.
</TEXT>
