<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     03-05 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistani Prime Minister Urges Moslems to Ignore Rushdie Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Rushdie Debate, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan said
Sunday that Moslems should have ignored ``The Satanic Verses,''
because controversy has brought the novel publicity, but she also
said the book should be banned.
   A radical Palestinian leader, Ahmed Jibril, vowed every effort to
kill Rushdie ``in defense of relgion, God, and his prophet.''
   Iranian media hinted a compromise was possible in Iran's
diplomatic standstill with Britain over the book, which some say
insults Islam.
   Ms. Bhutto, speaking on the British Broadcasting Corp. phone-in
show ``It's Your World,'' said, ``I do feel that the fundamentalists
have spread Rushdie's blasphemy.''
   ``Because what somebody writes (that) is not known, who cares
about that blasphemy? ... Perhaps it would have been more
appropriate to ignore such a book, to condemn it,'' she said.
   Ms. Bhutto came to power three months ago. She noted that the
previous Pakistani government had banned Rushdie's book but added,
``I don't think it has so much (to do) with Rushdie or the book, but
I think they just wanted a pretext to create a law and order
situation and to create anarchy.''
   However, she agreed that the book should be outlawed. Her country
is one of at least nine that have banned ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``I to think there are rare exceptions when the state has to
intervene ... balancing the freedom of expression and balancing the
security and the lives of the citizens,'' Ms. Bhutto said of the ban.
   Demonstrations against the book have killed 19 people in Pakistan
and India.
   Rushdie, a British citizen who was born into a Moslem family in
India, has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini sentenced him to death.
   In Damascus, Syria, Jibril said his Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command will make every effort to
carry out the death order.
   Although a staunch Marxist, Jibril said Rushdie's book was ``a
new conspiracy... a desperate attempt to defame God and his
prophet.''
   Jibril, a former Syrian army capital, leads about 1,000 fighters
based in Syria and Syrian-controlled provinces in neighboring
Lebanon. Jibril's statement was distributed to Syrian news offices.
   The Tehran Times, Iran's main English publication, suggested in
an editorial Sunday a ``change'' was possible in the deteriorating
relations between Britain and Iran.
   It referred to statements by British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher and her foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, acknowledging
the ``The Satanic Verses'' was insulting to Moslems.
   ``It may still be possible for a change to occur in view of the
new attitude which the British leaders are beginning to adopt, even
though slowly and late,'' the newspaper said in an editorial
reported by Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency.
   ``Whether the changes in the air from the British side will be
enough to satisfy the Iranian government is yet to be seen,'' the
paper said.
   In its own commentary, however, IRNA said the statements from
Mrs. Thatcher and Howe are ``far from meeting the conditions set by
the Majlis (parliament).''
   ``The withdrawal of all copies of `The Satanic Verses' and
banning of its reprinting by the British government would certainly
bring London closer to implentation of the Iranian conditions,'' the
news service said.
   The Iranian Parliament voted Tuesday to break relations with
Britain unless Britain within a week reversed its decision to
withdraw diplomats from Iran. Britain has protested Khomeini's death
call and demanded it be rescinded.
</TEXT>
