<FIRST>r a AM-LiquorLobbying     03-05 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liquor Lobbying,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Calls From Mormon Officials Doom Bill, But Reactions
Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The way state Sen. Kay Cornaby tells it,
the last-minute call from a Mormon Church official about a pending
liquor bill was no more than a mild suggestion that the measure
needed further study.
   But that and similar calls to other state senators at the hectic
finale of the 1989 Legislature last month apparently doomed the
bill, prompting accusations of illegal interference and forcing the
temperance-minded church to defend its right to speak out on what it
views as moral issues.
   The measure, which easily won House approval and was pending in
the Senate, would have formally legalized a decades-old practice of
allowing adult passengers in limousines and charter buses to drink
alcoholic beverages.
   ``The request that I got, was if it hit the Senate, to take a
close look and evaluate what effect it might have,'' said Cornaby.
   But Rusty Andersen, owner of Image Limousines, contends the calls
amounted to an unconstitutional mingling of church and state, and
illegal contact by unregistered lobbyists.
   He's threatened lawsuits on both issues.
   ``Senators are duly elected officials. They are of the people and
for the people,'' he said. ``This is a case of `of the church and
for the church.'''
   That view prompted the Utah chapter of the American Civil
Liberties Union to defend Utah's predominant religion, saying its
representatives have a right to express opinions on legislative
matters.
   Cornaby and several other Republicans were called by Richard P.
Lindsay and Bill Evans of the church's public communications
department.
   Lindsay said Friday that church officials had recommended to
legislative leaders during a routine pre-session briefing that any
measure involving liquor undergo detailed study.
   The last-minute calls, he said, merely reiterated that position.
   In an editorial Wednesday, The Salt Lake Tribune labeled the
calls an inappropriate ``end run'' of the statutory process for
influencing legislation. The newspaper said the church already had a
registered lobbyist, Oscar McConkie, and that such contacts were
within his province.
   Lindsay denied the calls constituted lobbying and said McConkie
was ill and unavailable at the time.
   The Utah lobbyist law holds that anyone who receives
contributions or compensation for the ``purpose of attempting to
influence the passage or defeat of any legislation'' must register
with the state.
   But Associate Chief Deputy Attorney General David Thomas said
last week that Lindsay and Evans were ``technically within the law''
because neither received additional compensation beyond their normal
church salaries.
   It is by no means the first time officials of the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, which strongly discourages use of
alcohol, tobacco, coffee or tea, have tendered opinions on liquor
legislation.
   Indeed, lawmakers frequently have sought the church's opinion on
proposed changes in Utah's strict drinking laws.
   This case involved a tradition in which limo and bus operators,
especially those running ``gambler specials'' to Wendover, Nev.,
have allowed patrons to take along beer or spirits.
   The practice was halted last summer when the Utah attorney
general's office decided it violated a law banning open containers
in motor vehicles.
   The measure to legalize the practice was approved by a 53-20
House vote after supporters argued that it would keep drunken
drivers off the road and that defeat would hurt tourism by
bolstering outsiders' beliefs that Utah is an inhospitable place.
   The bill had the support of the state Department of Public Safety
and Gov. Norm Bangerter, a Mormon.
   The measure was never debated because Senate President Arnold
Christensen, who also was called, would not recognize the sponsor,
Sen. Omar Bunnell.
   ``This is a bit of a tempest in a teapot, I think,'' said Bunnell
later. ``I just think the church could have done a better job of
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
