<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan 1stLd-Writethru a0684 03-05 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CAIRO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says He'll Form New Government To Help End War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Mahdi comments, fundamentalists possibly
staying in govt. No pickup. Changes byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi bowed to
political and military pressure Sunday and said he is forming a new
government in hopes of ending the nearly 6-year-old civil war.
   Mahdi made the announcement after signing a ``national peace
declaration'' with other political leaders that endorses a tentative
peace agreement with the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army of
John Garang.
   At a news conference, Mahdi also announced the fundamentalist
National Islamic Front had expressed a willingness to join the new
government. It had refused to sign the peace declaration.
   There was no immediate reaction from the rebels, who are mainly
Christian and animist and are demanding political and economic
reforms from the mainly Moslem government.
   The military had demanded Mahdi sign the cease-fire agreement.
The armed forces did not say what they would do if Mahdi did not
sign, but Mahdi had threatened to resign unless the army promised
not to overthrow him and union leaders pledged not to strike.
   The announcment came on the deadline Mahdi gave for his
resignation.
   Earlier, the Middle East News Agency in Cairo quoted Mahdi as
saying he would stay in office because the military and the
professional and trade unions had assured him of their support.
   He said his Cabinet ministers offered him their resignations and
that the new broad-based government would be announced ``in the
shortest time possible.''
   ``The new government will be formed with the aim of establishing
the largest amount of unity on the internal front,'' Mahdi said.
   He also promised a general election but did not say when it would
be held. The next scheduled election is in 1992.
   He said the new government would concentrate on the ``quick
support'' of the armed forces, which in recent months have lost
several towns to the rebels.
   Mahdi said the armed forces sent him a memo Sunday supporting the
constitution and the democratic process.
   He said ``ongoing contacts'' were under way to organize a meeting
``to resolve the peace issue.'' He did not elaborate.
   On Saturday night, Mahdi and 60 political and union leaders,
signed a program for the new government and the ``national peace
declaration.''
   Under the agreement, the new government must endorse a tentative
peace plan signed Nov. 16 between the rebels and the Democratic
Unionist Party, the second-largest party after Mahdi's Umma Party.
   The peace plan calls for an immediate cease-fire and end to the
state of emergency, and a conference with all political parties and
the rebels to negotiate a new government.
   Mahdi's failure to endorse it prompted the Democratic Unionists
to quit the coalition government in December. Mahdi then formed a
new government with the Islamic Front, which rejected peace talks
because the rebels are mainly Christian and animist.
   The rebels have fought since 1983 and won several victories in
recent months. Last month, they captured Torit, the second largest
garrison in the south.
</TEXT>
