<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Travelers Bjt   03-05 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Travelers, Bjt,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Passengers Run Aground As Strike Sullies Peak Florida Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Travelers slept on their luggage in airport lobbies,
stood in lines of confusion, argued over transfers and cursed the
labor fiasco that left them stranded Sunday on the second day of the
Eastern Airlines strike.
   Would-be passengers learned firsthand the hassle of going places
during an airline strike, particularly in Eastern's hometown at the
height of the Caribbean cruise trade and South Florida's tourist
season.
   John Vannua of Long Island, N.Y., defined the issue, and none too
delicately, for passengers at Miami International Airport.
   ``I'm not flying this stinking airline again!'' he yelled as he
tore up his Eastern frequent-flier card. He and three friends had
been waiting three hours to have their tickets validated by Eastern
for flights on other carriers.
   Eastern apologized Sunday for inconveniences suffered by its
passengers.
   ``We are placing the emphasis on protecting the cruise
passengers, the Caribbean routes and the Northeast shuttle,'' said
company spokesman Robin Matell. ``The handling of passengers is
below what we would like.''
   He admitted the airline has not been able to find lodging for all
passengers.
   ``We've been able to put many in hotels, but it's Grand Prix
weekend and the hotels are totally booked,'' he said. This is the
height of South Florida's tourist season with the Honda Classic PGA
tournament in Broward County, the Florida Derby and baseball spring
training.
   Miami International Airport, referred to somewhat fondly as Mondo
Airport, raises chaos to an art form on a normal day. That was
compounded Sunday by the strike.
   Anxious passengers peppered frazzled Eastern employees in
Spanish, French, Haitian Creole and English.
   ``Nobody knows nothing,'' said 33-year-old Charlie Rink of
Philadelphia. ``There's nobody walking around talking to people to
explain things. They need a troubleshooter.''
   In San Juan, Puerto Rico, about 300 cruise ship passengers who
had booked Eastern flights to the mainland were stranded late
Saturday at Munoz Marin International Airport. Cruise ship tourists
frequently end their cruise in San Juan, where they return to the
United States by air.
   ``We managed to get all those passengers out, either on Eastern
flights or with other airlines. The last of them left for Miami on
an (Eastern) Airbus at 11 p.m.,'' said Eastern spokesman Arnaldo
Deleo, adding that Sunday the airline ``chartered four planes from
Continental for cruise ship passengers.''
   At Washington's National Airport, Karen Palmer, Eastern customer
service representative, tried to help passengers.
   ``Everything is crazy,'' she said. ``They're canceling (flights)
as we go along. Other airlines are working with us. We're going to
do the best we can with what we have. ... I need a cocktail.''
   For Larry Palmer, arriving in New York on an Eastern flight at
1:30 a.m. Saturday after his original flight was canceled, it meant
being stuck at Kennedy International Airport. ``After the strike is
over, I'll write a letter of complaint and bill them for my extra
expenses.''
   While many passengers were cranky, others were understanding.
   ``I'm a little disappointed, but they've been very helpful. I
think the people behind the desk are doing a great job,'' said Sue
Carroll, 59, of Santa Ana, Calif., who was headed to Tampa for a
relative's funeral.
   Ms. Carroll was rescheduled for a flight three hours later on
Continental, Eastern's sister carrier, also owned by Texas Air Corp.
   Most airlines are helping Eastern, except for TWA, Eastern
spokesman Jim Ashlock said Sunday.
   ``TWA is not helping at all; American takes passengers on
standby; Pan American takes passengers on standby; United has been
helping depending on availability, either booking them on or
standby; Delta has got the same pattern; USAir and Piedmont have the
same policy,'' Ashlock said. ``Continental is taking everything.''
   In a designated area of Miami International, 32-year-old
Machinist Ray Rehill handed out informational pamphlets and watched
passengers scurrying about.
   ``I feel sorry for these people,'' he said, but he added, ``Their
day of inconvenience is my whole life. I've got a child and wife to
support.''
</TEXT>
