<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     03-05 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>50 Guerrillas, 8 Indians Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian troops searching a northeastern
jungle for rebel hideouts killed 50 Tamil guerrillas, a senior
Indian diplomat said Sunday. The Indians lost eight men, including
an army colonel.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
guerrillas were killed when the Indians raided sites near
Mullaitivu, 120 miles northeast of Colombo, the capital.
   ``Reports I have before me indicate at least 50 Tamil Tiger
rebels died in the assault'' the Indian diplomat said.
   He said the Indian offensive was launched to clear the jungles of
Tamil Tigers who have regularly made forays into nearby villages to
massacre unarmed Sinhalese civilians.
   ``The Indian operation, yet going on, does not involve the Sri
Lankan army. We are searching jungles for the guerrillas and will
continue until we flush them out'' the diplomat said.
   Tamil who make 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people allege
they are discriminated by the majority Sinhalese who form about 75
percent of the overall population of the island off India's southern
coast. Moderate Tamils want autonomy _ while the Tigers are fighting
for independence _ for predominantly Tamil areas of the north and
east.
   In another incident, a Sri Lankan military official in Colombo
said a mine blew up a jeep carrying Sri Lankan sailors Saturday,
killing five and injuring one in Trincomalee, 147 miles northeast of
Colombo.
   On Thursday, Ranjan Wijeratne, foreign affairs and deputy defense
minister told reporters in Colombo that plans were afoot to launch a
joint Indian-Sri Lankan military operation to flush out Tamil Tigers
hiding in caves in dense jungles in northeastern Sri Lanka.
   This was after marauding Tamil Tiger rebels were accused of
massacring 81 Sinhalese villagers in three attacks on poorly guarded
settlements in the northeast during February.
   The worst came February 27 when Tamil rebels shot and hacked to
death 38 Sinhalese, including nine children.
   But the Indian diplomat said the operation was being conducted
only by the Indians.
   India has an estimated 40,000 troops in Sri Lanka to enforce a
New Delhi-brokered peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil separarist
war.
</TEXT>
