<FIRST>r a AM-Congressman-Contras     03-05 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressman-Contras,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rep. Montgomery Says Contras Need Help, and Now</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN EVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress needs to restore military aid to
the rebels battling Nicaragura's leftist government, a congressman
said Sunday following a visit with 15,000 Contra troops in Honduras.
   ``Congress should not only continue giving humanitarian aid (to
the Contras) who are fighting the communists, but should also
restore military funding,'' Rep. G.V. Montgomery, D-Miss., said in a
telephone interview from Washington.
   Montgomery led a six-member bipartisan House delegation that
spent two days on the Nicaraguran-Hondouran border last week meeting
with the Contras at their base camps.
   ``Congress has created a real problem by not approving more
military aid to the freedom figthers,'' Montgomery said.
   Congress voted in February 1988 to cut off military aid but
agreed to continue $27 million in humanitarian aid for food and
medicine until April.
   ``They are a fine fighting force, but it is a whole new ball game
for them now because of the lack of military aid,'' Montgomery said
of the Contras. ``They just don't have the means to keep fighting.
   ``The fight is at a standstill. They lack ammunition to keep
fighting. Something has got to be done,'' he said. ``Their spirits
are excellent, and their numbers haven't decreased. In fact, they
are gaining more troops.
   ``But in May when the food stops coming, who knows what will
happen.''
   Montgomery said the delegation discussed options, including
bringing the Contras to the United States, or joining the Honduran
government in forcing them back into Nicaragua to survive the best
way they can.
   He said the group agreed that the best option is to push for
continuing humanitarian aid and to ask Congress for new military aid.
   ``We created the Contras to overthrow the Communists in
Nicaragua, and I don't think we should walk away from that
commitment,'' Montgomery said.
   Joining Montgomery on the trip were Reps. Bob Stump, R-Ariz.,
John Paul Hammerschmidt, R-Ark.; Floyd Harris, D-Ala.; Earl Hutto,
D-Fla., and Bob McEwen, R-Idaho.
</TEXT>
