<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     03-05 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0340</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Saddam Urges POW Exchange To Free All Captives ^By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein said Sunday that
Iraq is ready to repatriate all of its Iranian prisoners of war if
Tehran agrees to free the Iraqis it holds, Baghdad Radio reported.
   The state-run radio quoted Saddam as saying that the POW swap
could be carried out independently of the stalled talks over ending
the 8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Baghdad Radio quoted Saddam as saying at a meeting with Hans
Coshler, president of the Vienna-based International Progress
Organization, a human rights group, that ``Iraq, for humanitarian
and legal reasons, is fully ready to start a total exchange of
prisoners with Iran.''
   A comprehensive POW exchange would be a major breakthrough that
could break the deadlock in implementing a U.N. resolution that is
the basis for the current cease-fire.
   Iran and Iraq have been bickering since the peace talks began
Aug. 25 over how to implement the cease-fire resolution, which calls
for each nation to withdraw to their pre-war borders, an exchange of
prisoners of war and forming a special panel to assess blame for the
war.
   The two sides have released a few hundred ailing and disabled
prisoners since the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
   But a full exchange has been held up because of the deadlock in
the peace talks.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross has registered
50,812 prisoners held by Iran and 19,284 Iranians in Iraqi hands.
But U.N. and other officials estimate the total number of POWs to be
about 100,000.
   Iran, which claims the Iraqis still occupy border areas, insists
that a troop withdrawals to the pre-war border should be the next
step in the peace process.
   But Iraq maintains that Iran must abandon its right to search
Iraq-bound ships in international waters of the gulf for war cargo.
Iran has not stopped any ships since the cease-fire took effect, but
reserves the right to do so.
</TEXT>
