<SECOND>AM-Lightning-Deaths,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Children Killed In House Fire Sparked By Lightning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSSELLVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning sparked a house fire Sunday
that killed a 7-year-old boy and his teen-age sister, but their
father saved his wife and two younger children by hurling them out a
second-story window, authorities said.
   The lightning ``came down through a tree'' and tore through the
wood-frame home's tin roof around 5:50 a.m., said fire Lt. Jerry
Boyd.
   ``Several neighbors said it sounded like a dynamite explosion and
immediately they heard some people scream,'' Boyd said.
   The family was sleeping upstairs when the fire broke out, and the
blaze consumed the stairs, said Boyd.
   Elton King threw his 34-year-old wife, Ruby; 3-month-old
daughter, Kelli; and 4-year-old son, Nikki, out a window, the
lieutenant said.
   Firefighters who arrived a few minutes later found the home
engulfed in flames.
   They found the bodies of Elton Ray King Jr., 7, and Misty Dawn
Hatton King, 14, in their parents' bedroom, Boyd said. ``They just
didn't get out.''
   The father, who was burned, cut and bruised, and Mrs. King, who
also suffered cuts and bruises, were in satisfactory condition
Sunday at Humana Hospital in this northwest Alabama city, Boyd said.
Mrs. King was also being treated for a lung injury.
   Kelli and Nikki were treated at the hospital for cuts and
released to relatives.

