<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   03-05 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0731,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police and Teen-age Protesters Clash in Gdansk</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS seven grafs after 8th, `The crowd...' to UPDATE with
Politburo member's comments on status of talks, details on political agreement;
picks up 9th pvs: In Lodz...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police wielding truncheons clashed Sunday
with 500 stone-throwing teen-agers in Gdansk following a Mass in
which Solidarity leader Lech Walesa appealed for moderation, a
witness said.
   About 10 people were arrested in the 40-minute clash in Gdansk,
said a witness connected with St. Brygida's Church. The witness
described the events in a telephone interview and spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Before the protest, supporters of the radical Fighting Solidarity
splinter group handed out leaflets accusing Walesa of selling out
the banned Solidarity movement in his talks with the government,
according to the witness.
   Walesa responded by saying there was room in Poland for all
groups and defended his negotiating position at talks with
authorities, which enter their fifth week Monday.
   ``I have chosen maybe a naive alternative in order to achieve
reforms at the least price. There is no revolution in the direction
we are going. We are entering an evolutionary path. You have to join
Walesa on this path whether you like it or not,'' Walesa said.
   After he spoke, demonstrators marched toward a nearby railway
station chanting, ``Solidarity!'' and ``Down with Communists!'' the
witness said.
   People began throwing money at police saying, ``Don't beat your
brother for money.'' Police ordered the crowd to disperse, to no
avail. They then moved in to break up the demonstration, the witness
said.
   The crowd pelted the officers with stones, and police responded
by rushing protesters and beating them with truncheons, he said.
   The opposition and the government have been meeting since Feb. 6
to discuss reaching a broad concensus on economic and political
reforms. The talks, an outgrowth of Poland's crippled economy and a
rash of labor unrest, may lead to legalization of Solidarity, which
was outlawed after the 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   The talks enter their fifth week Monday with an intensive series
of negotiations planned to resolve the issue of opposition
participation in elections to parliament, which the communist party
would like to hold in June.
   Both sides already have agreed that the elections will not be
fully democratic, instead guaranteeing that a majority of the 460
parliament seats will be open only to candidates from the communist
party and its allies.
   Now they are debating the format for the remaining races which
will be open to Solidarity and other non-aligned candidates. It has
been agreed that anyone may run who has collected 3,000 nominating
signatures.
   Party Politburo member Janusz Reykowski told The Associated Press
on Sunday that the discussions on political reform have entered a
critical phase.
   ``We are now, I would say, in a certain turning point. In the
last few days we have had very intensive meetings,'' he said.
   ``We are in the middle,'' he said. ''I hope that in the second
half of this week we will have a much more clear picture of what
really can be achieved in this process.''
   In Lodz, central Poland, supporters of the banned Independent
Students' Association demonstrated to mark the anniversary of March
8, 1968, student riots, state television reported.
   The nationalist Confederation for an Independent Poland meanwhile
held a congress to elect new leaders in a church in southern Krakow
city, said spokesman Zygmunt Lenyk. Police kept the meeting under
surveillance, he said.
   Police broke up a previous attempt to hold the congress just
before the start of talks on Poland's future between the opposition
and the government.
   Lenyk said Leszek Moczulski, who founded the anti-communist group
in 1979, was elected chairman of a 12-member political council. The
small but vocal movement opposes dialogue with the authorities.
</TEXT>
