<FIRST>r i AM-France-Cesars     03-05 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Cesars,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adjani, Belmondo Awarded Cesars for Best Acting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Isabelle Adjani took best actress award at France's
14th annual Cesar film awards for her performance in ``Camille
Claudel'' and in a symbolic gesture read from ``The Satanic Verses''
in her acceptance speech.
   Jean-Paul Belmondo, who said in advance that he would refuse an
award, was acclaimed best actor at the Saturday night ceremonies for
his role in ``Itineraire d'un Enfant Gate'' (Itinerary of a Spoiled
Child).
   ``Camille Claudel,'' which received a total of five Cesars, was
voted best film of the year. It also won the categories of best
photography, decor and costumes.
   Ms. Adjani, who has received two other Cesars for best actress,
has shown a special attachment to her role as the sculptress Camille
Claudel, the tragic lover of sculptor Auguste Rodin. In accepting
the award, Adjani referred to her as ``an artist too quickly
excluded by others.''
   Ms. Adjani, of French and Algerian extraction, then read several
lines from ``The Satanic Verses'' of Salman Rushdie, who has been in
hiding since Iranian clerics issued death threats last month, saying
his book blasphemes Islam.
   ``You should know what I have suffered. ... In the artist's
condition there is something extreme,'' she read. ``Angels are easy
to calm. Human beings ... can doubt everything.''
   There was little overt reaction from the audience at the
recitation, and she accepted her award and left the stage.
   Belmondo, 55, who had never before been nominated for a Cesar but
has starred in numerous films including ``Au bout de souffle,''
(Breathless), has said the audience reaction to his work is reward
enough.
   Jean Jacques Annaud, whose ``L'Ours'' (The Bear) is the current
box office hit in France, was awarded a Cesar for best director.
   The West German film ``Baghdad Cafe'' directed by Percy Adlon was
voted best foreign film.
