<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planes Collide, Four Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASA GRANDE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two airplanes collided Sunday over the
desert seven miles west of the airport here, killing all three
people on one plane and the pilot of the second aircraft, officials
said.
   The collision occurred around 12:30 p.m., according to Cpl. Bruce
McGregor of the Pinal County Sheriff's Department.
   Officials said the planes involved were a Cessna carrying three
people that was believed to be from California and a small, red
single-seater from Phoenix, which is about 40 miles to the north.
   The Cessna burst into flames after hitting the ground, and the
bodies were so badly burned it was impossible to determine the
victims' sex, McGregor said.
   The Casa Grande Municipal Airport was the site this weekend of
the 31st annual Cactus Fly-in, which features antique and
experimental aircraft, but it was not known if the collision
involved planes from the event.
   The Pima County medical examiner scheduled autopsies for Monday.
