<HEAD>Easter Seals Telethon Passes Goal With Over $37 Million in Contributions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television viewers pledged more than $37
million to the National Easter Seal Society during its 18th annual
weekend telethon, the head of the non-profit organization said
Sunday.
   John Garrison, president and chief executive officer of the
Easter Seal, said this year's contributions totaled $37,002,000,
surpassing last year's mark of $35,100,000, and a goal of $36
million.
   ``We found that the American public was very supportive. We had
an even stronger turnout than we expected,'' Garrison said.
   The 20-hour 18th National Easter Seal Telethon, which aired live
from 8:00 p.m. Saturday to 4:00 p.m. Sunday on local television
stations nationwide, was hosted for the ninth year by singer Pat
Boone, and co-hosted by Mary Frann of CBS's ``Newhart'' and Robb
Weller of ``Entertainment Tonight.''
   Entertainers featured on the show included singers Tammy Wynette,
Mickey Gilley, Pia Zadora and Ray Charles. Debbie Boone joined the
host, her father, for a medley of their hits.
   The star of the show was 10-year-old Joy Hall, from Baltimore,
who is the National Easter Seal child. She was born with cerebral
palsy. Hall has already appeared on ``The Today Show,'' and will
guest star on the NBC series ``Amen'' later this year.
   Four corporations, Century 21, Safeway, Enesco and Amway,
contributed some $8 million to the cause, and became a part of the
``Million Dollar Club,'' said Garrison.
   The event was held at the Aquarius Theater here and an estimated
60 million people were expected to tune in.
