<HEAD>About 100 Arrested As Smoking Ban Takes Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 100 arrested, drivers urging riders to hide cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in Quezon City say they
arrested about 100 people on charges of violating a tough new
anti-smoking ordinance Sunday, the first day the law took effect.
   Under the new ordinance, smoking is banned in most public places,
including buses, restaurants, government offices, hospitals and
theaters in the city of about 1 million which is part of
metropolitan Manila.
   Violators who smoke in public places that are not designated
smoking zones face a $10 fine, 10 days in jail or both.
   City officials said they will put up signs along municipal
boundaries warning people they are entering ``a non-smoking city.''
   Drivers of passenger jeeps, the most common means of public
transport, urged riders to hide their cigarettes when they entered
Quezon City.
